{{Quote|Luke Skywalker&hellip; File: ZC-1905-FT, Section: OC-6492, Human: 10th Degree, Born: Sidereal Era, AS-5670&hellip; of Master and Mistress Tan Skywalker on&mdash;|Mistress Mnemos|<ref name="TCA">"[[The Constancia Affair]]"</ref>}}
'''Tan''' was a title-[[Military rank/Legends|rank]] that was bestowed to exceptionally skilled [[Pilot/Legends|pilots]] under the rule of [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]], [[Supreme Chancellor/Legends|Supreme Chancellor]] of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]]. It remained in use even after Palpatine [[Declaration of a New Order|appointed]] himself [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Galactic Emperor]] of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|New Order]]. Two well-known recipients of the special award were [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] [[Human/Legends|Humans]]. One was [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], a [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] who gained fame during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]]. The other was [[Maarek Stele/Legends|Maarek Stele]], who distinguished [[Gender/Legends|himself]] in the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] during the later [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]].

==Description==
Tan was both a [[Military rank/Legends|military rank]] and a honorary title<ref name="SWG5">{{GamerCite|5|The Emperor's Pawns}}</ref> awarded to [[Starfighter Corps/Legends|Starfighter Corps]] [[Officer/Legends|officers]] who had done their [[Head of State/Legends|Head of State]] a special service, in recognition of their exceptional [[Pilot/Legends|piloting]] skills.<ref name="V:UG" /> It was used as a honorific prefix to its bearer's surname,<ref name="SWG5" /> sometimes in combination with the [[Gender/Legends|masculine]] form of address "Master." Additionally, the [[Marriage/Legends|wife]] of a [[Gender/Legends|male]] recipient could also be referred to as "Mistress Tan" followed by her married name.<ref name="TCA" />

==History==
[[File:Stele_Old.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Tan Maarek Stele]]
The name and concept of Tan was created by [[Palpatine/Legends|Palpatine]], [[Supreme Chancellor/Legends|Supreme Chancellor]] of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]], during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]],<ref name="V:UG" /> a [[The galaxy/Legends|pan-galactic]] conflict that [[First Battle of Geonosis/Legends|started]] in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]].<ref name="NEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''</ref> Following the [[Mission to Mustafar/Legends|end]] of the war in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]], Palpatine [[Imperialization/Legends|transformed]] the Republic into a [[Galactic Empire/Legends|New Order]] and [[Declaration of a New Order|appointed himself]] [[Galactic Emperor/Legends|Galactic Emperor]].<ref name="Inaugural Edition">{{InsiderCite|84|Republic HoloNet News Special Inaugural Edition 16:5:241}}</ref> However, the title-rank Tan saw continued use under the [[New Order/Legends|new regime]].<ref name="SWG5" />

Among the individuals who earned the title, at least two were [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] [[Human/Legends|Human]] males. The first was [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], a [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] from [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]] who fought in the Clone Wars and was granted the title while [[Starfighter combat/Legends|flying]] a [[Anakin Skywalker's Eta-2 Actis-class interceptor/Legends|customized]] [[Eta-2 Actis-class interceptor/Legends|Eta-2 ''Actis''-class interceptor]]<ref name="V:UG" /> by [[20 BBY/Legends|20 BBY]].<ref name="Date" /> The second one was [[Maarek Stele/Legends|Maarek Stele]], a [[Kuan]]-born [[Ace/Legends|ace]] pilot who made a brilliant career in Palpatine's [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] during the [[Galactic Civil War/Legends|Galactic Civil War]], after he helped thwart an [[Zaarin insurrection|attempted coup]]<ref name="SWG5" /> in [[3 ABY/Legends|3.5 ABY]].<ref name="NEC" /> The fact that Skywalker had once held the title-rank appeared in the database of [[Mistress Mnemos]], a [[BRT supercomputer/Legends|BRT supercomputer]] that served in a [[Fusai library|library branch]] of the [[Obroa-skai/Legends|Obroa-skai]] [[Celebratus Archive]] located on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Fusai/Legends|Fusai]]. Mnemos once referred to him and his wife<ref name="TCA" /> [[Padmé Amidala/Legends|Padmé Amidala]]<ref name="AOC">{{Film|II}}</ref> as "Master and Mistress Tan Skywalker" in a file pertaining to their son, [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]].<ref name="TCA" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Tan Skywalker. It's a rather apt name for a man from the suns-baked world of Tatooine, wouldn't you say? But the 'tan' here doesn't refer to the golden glow of Anakin or Luke's skin. Instead, the name comes down to us from Star Wars writer and illustrator Russ Manning.|Abel G. Peña|<ref name="Pena" />}}
[[File:TanSkywalker-ConstanciaAffair.png|thumb|right|Tan Skywalker was mentioned in ''The Constancia Affair''.]]
The name of Tan originated with [[Russ Manning]], a ''[[Star Wars]]'' writer and illustrator who published numerous black-and-white newspaper [[Star Wars comic books|comic]] [[Star Wars (comic strip)|strips]] in the late 1970s and early 1980s.<ref name="Pena">{{Blog|abelgpena|42|The Anatomy of a Ret-Con 3: or, "That Name No Longer Has Any Meaning For Me"}}</ref> In one [[1978]] series of strips that was later titled ''[[The Constancia Affair]]'', Luke Skywalker's [[Parent/Legends|parents]] were called "Master and Mistress Tan Skywalker."<ref name="TCA" /> At the time, the [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] was in its early stages, and nobody knew the name of Luke's father, save that the two probably shared the surname Skywalker. The given name "Anakin" was only revealed in the [[1983]] movie [[Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi|''Star Wars'': Episode VI ''Return of the Jedi'']], five years after the release of ''The Constantia Affair''. In view of that new element, the dialogue mentioning Tan Skywalker became a [[Canon|continuity]] problem.<ref name="Pena" />

Another unexplained occurrence of the name appeared in ''[[TIE Fighter: The Official Strategy Guide]]'', the [[Prima Games]] companion to the [[1994]] [[Wikipedia:Personal computer|PC]] [[Star Wars video games|game]] [[Star Wars: TIE Fighter (video game)|of the same name]]. The publisher's summary on the guide's back flap stated that it "[continued] the story of Tan Stele's adventures." However, the hero of ''Star Wars: TIE Fighter'' was in fact named Maarek Stele, and was referred as such everywhere else in the strategy guide itself.<ref name="TF:OSG">''[[TIE Fighter: The Official Strategy Guide]]''</ref>

''Star Wars'' author [[Abel G. Peña]], who had pointed out those two anomalies, discussed the matter with his colleague [[Pablo Hidalgo]], who suggested that Tan was "some kind of title given to exceptional starfighter aces." Peña liked the idea and decided to endorse it. When he wrote his [[2001]] article ''[[The Emperor's Pawns]]'', he tied the two occurrences together, introducing a [[Retroactive continuity|retcon]] that established Tan as a title for exceptional pilots such as Maarek Stele.<ref name="SWG5" /> He also took the opportunity to apply the title to Anakin Skywalker in ''[[Vader Tech]]'', an article written for ''[[Vader: The Ultimate Guide]]'',<ref name="V:UG" /> hence explaining Mistress Mnemos' line in the 1978 comic strip. In [[2006]], Peña explained the history behind the retcon on his VIP [[Star Wars: Blogs|Star Wars Blog]], in a post titled "The Anatomy of a Ret-Con 3: or, "That Name No Longer Has Any Meaning For Me."<ref name="Pena" />

